[cite_start]``Lives on the Line'' provides a harrowing assessment of the immediate human cost resulting from the US administration's freeze on foreign aid and ``Stop Work'' orders[cite: 855]. [cite_start]The report details how the suspension of funding has forced the closure of life-saving services, putting millions at risk of death from untreated HIV, malaria, and pregnancy complications[cite: 864, 1072, 1094]. [cite_start]A key finding is the ``existential threat'' to local and national NGOs, who rely entirely on project funding and are now facing bankruptcy, legal liabilities, and the loss of community trust[cite: 883, 1353]. [cite_start]The report highlights the specific targeting of vulnerable groups, noting that the ban on ``gender ideology'' and DEI initiatives has cut off essential protection for women, children, and LGBTIQ+ populations[cite: 960, 1068]. [cite_start]Furthermore, the entire humanitarian infrastructure is degrading as coordination bodies and early warning systems like FEWS NET are defunded, leaving the global response ``blind'' to emerging famines[cite: 1397]. [cite_start]The study also notes a ``liquidity crisis'' where unpaid reimbursements from the US government are draining NGO reserves, forcing mass layoffs[cite: 1308, 1311]. [cite_start]Ultimately, ICVA warns that these policy shifts are not just a temporary pause but a dismantling of the principles of humanity and impartiality[cite: 1435, 1440].
source("~/.active-rstudio-document")
